{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504841"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:21:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:21:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2376"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2376"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.56,0.13,0.06,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2376"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57315"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2376"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2376"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42774"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"6563"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1503"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1569"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17566"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57315"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a check up. He is asymptomatic. His medical history includes type II diabetes, which is managed with metformin. He takes no other regular medications. On examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 76/min, blood pressure 142/96 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The physical examination reveals a left carotid bruit but is otherwise unremarkable. An ultrasound is ordered, which shows 65% stenosis of the left common carotid artery and 40% stenosis of the right common carotid.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["ACE inhibitor and high-dose statin","Aspirin, ACE inhibitor and high-dose statin","Dual anti-platelet therapy (DAPT)","Carotid stenting","Carotid endarterectomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis stem describes a patient with asymptomatic moderate left carotid artery stenosis (50-70%) and mild right stenosis (\u0026lt;50%), as well as uncontrolled hypertension. Asymptomatic carotid artery stenosis is associated with an annual stroke risk \u0026lt;1% and, given the inherent risk of stroke with carotid endarterectomy (CEA), medical management is preferred for patients with mild to moderate stenosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin, ACE inhibitor and high-dose statin\u003C/strong\u003E represent optimal medical management for this patient. The ACE inhibitor is particularly important given his elevated blood pressure of 142/96 mmHg. The statin will help stabilise any atherosclerotic plaques and prevent progression of stenosis. Aspirin provides antiplatelet cover for primary prevention. Adequate glycemic control is also important.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EACE inhibitor and high-dose statin\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient as antiplatelet therapy is an important component of prevention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDual anti-platelet therapy (DAPT)\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate only in the event of TIA or minor stroke, which this patient has not experienced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid endarterectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for symptomatic internal carotid artery stenosis \u0026gt;50%. Surgery for asymptomatic high-grade carotid stenoses is only indicated in highly-selected cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid stenting\u003C/strong\u003E is a higher risk alternative to endarterectomy, which may be used in the event that CEA is not feasible. It would not be appropriate in this asymptomatic patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Secondary prevention for asymptomatic carotid stenosis includes ACE inhibitor, high-dose statin and aspirin","Surgery is not indicated in asymptomatic carotid artery stenosis less than 70%","Blood pressure control is a key component of stroke prevention in carotid stenosis"],"references":["(Australian) Clinical Guidelines for Stroke Management - Chapter 4 of 8: Secondary prevention [Internet]. Stroke Foundation. 2021. Available from: https://app-test.magicapp.org/summary/guideline_4285.html","Managing asymptomatic carotid artery stenosis [Internet]. eTG Complete. 2017. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etgcomplete","Hackam DG. Optimal Medical Management of Asymptomatic Carotid Stenosis. Stroke. 2021 Jun;52(6):2191\u20138.","\u200c","\u200c"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42774"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2376"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42774"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-25T19:14:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-25T19:16:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2376"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57315"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}